Vendor Communication
Problem Statement, Strategic Context & Solution Proposal
Strategic Context
At the time of development, a strategic risk was becoming obvious:
Settly’s product value gets diluted whenever communication and documents move off-platform.
Settly’s differentiation is not “we can email vendors.”
It’s that we provide a central hub for relocation work: timelines, documents, milestones, next steps, and (increasingly) automation.
Two strategic drivers made this urgent:
Internationalisation Strategy (scale through vendor networks)

 As we expand internationally, we rely more on external vendors to deliver services in markets where we don’t have deep operational presence. A scalable vendor network becomes a first layer of international scaling.


Platform value and automation strategy

 A centralized workflow is the prerequisite to unlock:


automation (reminders, routing, status updates)


AI assistance (template generation, policy checks, summarisation, next-step recommendations)


operational control (shared visibility, fewer handovers breaking cases)


In other words: without centralization of communication + documents, Settly can’t fully behave like a platform.

My Role
As PM on Vendor Communication / Off-Platform Communications, I:
Mapped the end-to-end operational workflows (host ↔ vendor ↔ user ↔ client)


Defined the product strategy around centralisation first, automation second


Worked with Design and Engineering to prototype “plug into email” approaches


Structured a gradual transition plan to avoid breaking high-volume workflows


Drove decisions around what must be structured data (vendor directory, status) vs what can remain unstructured (emails, attachments)


My goal:
Move a critical workflow into the platform without forcing vendors to “join another tool.”

Product Context
Settly supports complex relocation cases that require daily coordination with a large vendor ecosystem.
In reality, we are dealing with:
hundreds of vendors across services


very uneven frequency: some vendors are used daily, others only a few times per year


unpredictable workflows based on vendor category, market, and internal vendor systems


A key constraint emerged early:
Onboarding every vendor to a platform is not feasible.
Vendors already operate in their own systems (ticketing tools, CRMs, reservation systems, shared inboxes). We needed to plug into existing workflows, not replace them.
At the same time, current internal workflows for hosts were fragmented:
communication lives across multiple inboxes and threads


information and context are split between the Settly platform, spreadsheets, policies, and email chains


hosts constantly switch tools and copy/paste case information back and forth


This creates operational drag, errors, and reduced visibility for anyone not sitting inside that host’s inbox.

Problem Identification
1) Fragmentation destroys platform value
When vendor communication happens in email, Settly loses the “hub” effect:
the platform stops being the source of truth


documents scatter across inboxes and drives


case progress becomes harder to understand for other stakeholders


This is especially harmful internationally, where we need the platform to provide structure and confidence across unfamiliar markets.
2) Vendors can’t be forced to change behavior
We operate in a world where:
some vendors interact through shared inboxes


others spawn entirely new email threads later in the process


many are backed by internal systems that reduce predictability


This makes “perfect” communication orchestration unrealistic.
We need resilient workflows that can tolerate messy vendor behaviors.
3) Internal teams suffer from switch-tasking and manual transfer
Hosts often have to:
manually copy case details from the platform into emails


chase approvals and replies across multiple threads


update statuses manually back in the platform


reconcile vendor information across spreadsheets, policies, and emails 


This creates:
high operational load


inconsistent tracking


loss of continuity when hosts are out of office


4) Inconsistent vendor data compounds the problem
Vendor information is stored in inconsistent formats and locations (spreadsheets, policies, drive folders), forcing hosts to cross-check multiple sources to find the right vendor and context. 
This becomes a scaling blocker as vendor complexity increases across markets.
5) This is a high-volume, unpredictable workflow → transition must be gradual
Vendor comms is not a “nice-to-have flow.”
It’s a critical operational workflow with:
high volume


high variance


real consequences if something breaks


So the move to platform-native communication had to be incremental and controlled, not a big-bang migration.

Activities
To solve this, I led work across three tracks:
Discovery & workflow mapping


mapped current vendor communication patterns (relay vs direct workflows)


captured failure modes: new threads, missing CCs, handovers, lost context


System design & product definition


defined what needed to become structured (vendor entities, status, linking to cases/services)


defined what could remain unstructured but centralized (email content, attachments, replies)


Feasibility exploration


validated that “email-first integration” could work technically and operationally


explored how to create reliable linking between vendor emails and case threads



The Solution
We designed the solution around a core principle:
Centralize communication and documents inside Settly, while letting vendors keep using email.
1) Plug into existing workflows with email-based threading
Instead of onboarding vendors onto Settly, we connected communication flows through:
email initiation from within the platform


vendor replies captured back into the platform thread


shared visibility across the internal team (instead of trapped in one host inbox)


This directly addresses the reality that vendor systems and habits are unpredictable.
2) Centralize documents as part of the communication loop
The user (and hosts) can share documents from the platform vault into the vendor conversation—reducing re-uploading and scattered attachments.
This reinforces the “hub” model:
the platform holds documents


communication references the platform’s source of truth


3) Templates + variables to remove copy/paste behavior
Initiation emails can be generated using templates with case variables, reducing manual assembly and improving consistency.
4) Gradual rollout with host-controlled activation
Because this is a high-stakes workflow, the rollout strategy was deliberately conservative:
release into production


let hosts decide when to activate user ↔ vendor comms via platform


start with pilot users where we can guarantee app version compatibility


expand usage once stability is validated


This aligns with the principle that transition must happen gradually.
5) Vendor management foundation
In parallel, we anchored the system in structured vendor data so that:
vendors can be connected to companies/services


preferred vendors can be surfaced


later automation/reporting becomes possible


This directly addresses the “reconciling across spreadsheets/policies/email” issue. 

Outcome & Early Signals
From stakeholder feedback and early rollout signals:
The platform approach enables centralization without vendor onboarding friction


It unlocks a pathway to automation and AI leverage because communication is now “in-system”


Early adoption signal: ~70% of vendors added to the platform had email communication connected (with remaining edge cases to solve through workflow coverage and operational rollout)



Why This Initiative Mattered
This project wasn’t “an email feature.”
It was a strategic enabler for:
International scaling: vendor network becomes the delivery layer; Settly remains the coordination layer


Platform value retention: keep documents + conversations + next steps in one hub


Automation and AI leverage: once comms is centralized, we can add reminders, summarisation, policy checks, routing, and proactive assistance


Operational resilience: reduce dependence on individual inboxes and reduce handover risk


In short:
Centralisation of communication and documents is a prerequisite for scaling Settly internationally and for unlocking the next wave of AI-driven operational control.


